                <p class="description">
                    The Army War College, Mhow (AWC) is the Indian Army's premier institution for strategic leadership education and operational doctrine development. Located in Mhow, Madhya Pradesh, it functions as a centre of excellence in military training, research, and education. Originally established as the College of Combat in 1971, the institution was renamed in 2003 and has since evolved into a hub for developing senior leadership across the Indian Armed Forces.
                </p>

                <p class="description">
                    Each year, the college trains approximately 2500–3000 officers from the Indian Army, paramilitary forces, and friendly foreign nations. Its core mission is to prepare military leaders to operate in complex strategic environments, develop modern warfare doctrines, and synchronize joint operations with other services. The Higher Command Course offered here is affiliated with Devi Ahilya Vishwavidyalaya (Indore University) and is part of an M.Phil. in Defence Management.
                </p>

                <p class="description">
                    The college is led by the Commandant, a three-star general officer. It also publishes the <em>War College Journal</em> and was honored with the GOC-in-C ARTRAC Unit Citation in 2014. With modern infrastructure, wargaming facilities, and a dedicated faculty, the Army War College continues to shape the future of military leadership and doctrine for India and its allies.
                </p>

